Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 Information Geometry

Let \mathcal{P}(X) denote the space of probability measures on a sample space X. A statistical model is a parametrized family \{p_\theta \mid \theta \in \Theta\} where \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n is open. Under regularity conditions, \Theta carries a natural Riemannian metric: the Fisher information metric

g_{ij}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}\left[ \partial_i \log p_\theta \, \partial_j \log p_\theta \right] = \int p_\theta(x) \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta^i} \frac{\partial \log p_\theta(x)}{\partial \theta^j} dx.

For exponential families p_\theta(x) = \exp(\theta \cdot T(x) - \psi(\theta)), the Fisher metric is the Hessian of the log partition function: g_{ij}(\theta) = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta).

The Kullback‑Leibler divergence

D_{KL}(p \parallel q) = \int p(x) \log \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} dx

generates both the metric (via its second derivative) and a dual pair of affine connections (\nabla, \nabla^*) that make (\Theta, g, \nabla, \nabla^*) a dually flat space (Amari, 1985). In dually flat spaces, geodesics are straight lines in the natural or expectation parameters, and the divergence satisfies a generalized Pythagorean theorem.

Shannon entropy H(p) = -\mathbb{E}_p[\log p] will serve as our regularization functional. Its gradient with respect to the Fisher metric has a simple form for exponential families: \text{grad}_g H = -(\theta - \theta_0) for some reference parameter \theta_0.

Proposition 2.1 (Strong convexity of regularized loss). For an exponential family in natural parameters, the negative entropy -H is 1‑strongly geodesically convex with respect to the Fisher metric. Consequently, for any \lambda > 0, the regularized loss \mathcal{L}_\lambda = \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} - \lambda H is \lambda-strongly geodesically convex if \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} is geodesically convex (i.e., its Hessian is positive semidefinite).

Proof. In natural parameters, the Fisher metric is constant: g_{ij} = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta). The Hessian of -H with respect to g is the identity matrix (Amari, 1998). Hence \nabla_g^2 (-\lambda H) = \lambda I. Adding a convex function preserves strong convexity with at least the same modulus. ∎

2.2 Category Theory

A category \mathbf{C} consists of objects \text{Ob}(\mathbf{C}) and morphisms \text{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}(A,B) for each pair A,B, with composition \circ and identities \text{id}_A. A functor F: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{D} maps objects to objects and morphisms to morphisms preserving composition and identities. A natural transformation \alpha: F \Rightarrow G is a family of morphisms \alpha_A: F(A) \to G(A) in \mathbf{D} such that for any f: A \to B in \mathbf{C}, \alpha_B \circ F(f) = G(f) \circ \alpha_A.

A monad on \mathbf{C} is a triple (T, \eta, \mu) with T: \mathbf{C} \to \mathbf{C} an endofunctor, \eta: \text{Id}_{\mathbf{C}} \Rightarrow T (unit) and \mu: T^2 \Rightarrow T (multiplication) satisfying:

· \mu \circ T\eta = \mu \circ \eta T = \text{id}_T
· \mu \circ T\mu = \mu \circ \mu T

The Kleisli category \mathbf{C}_T has the same objects as \mathbf{C}, but morphisms A \to B are morphisms A \to T(B) in \mathbf{C}. Composition is Kleisli composition: g \circ_T f = \mu_Z \circ T(g) \circ f.

2.3 Gradient Flows and Geodesic Convexity

On a Riemannian manifold (M,g), the gradient flow of a smooth function \mathcal{L}: M \to \mathbb{R} is the curve \theta(t) satisfying

\dot{\theta}(t) = -\text{grad}_g \mathcal{L}(\theta(t)),

where \text{grad}_g \mathcal{L} is the unique vector field such that g(\text{grad}_g \mathcal{L}, X) = d\mathcal{L}(X) for all X. In coordinates, (\text{grad}_g \mathcal{L})^i = g^{ij} \partial_j \mathcal{L}.

A function \mathcal{L} is geodesically convex if for any geodesic \gamma: [0,1] \to M,

\mathcal{L}(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t)\mathcal{L}(\gamma(0)) + t\mathcal{L}(\gamma(1)).

It is \mu-strongly geodesically convex if

\mathcal{L}(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t)\mathcal{L}(\gamma(0)) + t\mathcal{L}(\gamma(1)) - \frac{\mu}{2} t(1-t) d(\gamma(0),\gamma(1))^2.

For \mu-strongly convex functions on complete manifolds, gradient flows converge exponentially to the unique minimizer (if it exists).

2.4 Ricci Curvature and Stability

The Ricci curvature \text{Ric}(v,v) measures the average sectional curvature in directions containing v. A lower bound on Ricci curvature implies that geodesics tend to converge (positive Ricci) or diverge (negative Ricci). In control theory, Ricci curvature appears in comparison theorems (Bakry–Émery) that control the growth of Lyapunov functions along flows.

2.5 Cencov’s Theorem and Stochastic Maps

Cencov’s theorem (Čencov, 1982) states that the Fisher metric is the unique Riemannian metric (up to scaling) on the simplex of probability distributions that is invariant under congruent embeddings by Markov morphisms. A corollary: Markov kernels (stochastic maps) are contractions of the Fisher metric when the domain and codomain are equipped with the Fisher geometry. More precisely, for any Markov kernel k: M \to N, the induced push‑forward satisfies k_*^* g_N \preceq g_M. This provides a rigorous justification for information‑contracting morphisms in our category.

