Chapter 5: Reduction to Known Architectures

5.1 Natural Gradient Descent

If we set \lambda = 0, the intentional flow reduces to

\dot{\theta} = -F(\theta)^{-1} \nabla \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}.

This is exactly the natural gradient descent algorithm introduced by Amari (1998). By Proposition 2.1, if \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} is convex, then \mathcal{L}_0 is geodesically convex, and Theorem 4.2 guarantees exponential convergence.

5.2 Transformers as Fisher‑Contracting Maps

We now analyze a transformer attention layer and prove it is a contracting morphism in Stat with an explicit bound on metric distortion.

Proposition 5.1 (Attention is Fisher‑contracting). Let M be a statistical manifold of token embeddings (each token represented by a Gaussian distribution with fixed covariance, or more generally any exponential family). Consider an attention head with parameters Q,K,V and softmax activation. The map \text{Attn}: M^n \to M^n defined by

\text{Attn}(\theta_1,\dots,\theta_n)_i = \sum_{j=1}^n \alpha_{ij}(\theta) \theta_j,

where \alpha_{ij}(\theta) = \frac{\exp(\langle Q\theta_i, K\theta_j\rangle / \sqrt{d})}{\sum_k \exp(\langle Q\theta_i, K\theta_k\rangle / \sqrt{d})}, is a Markov kernel in each coordinate (since it outputs a convex combination of input distributions). By Cencov’s theorem, any Markov kernel is a contraction of the Fisher metric. Consequently, \text{Attn} is a morphism in Stat with Lipschitz constant L \le 1 with respect to the product Fisher metric.

Proof. The map \text{Attn} sends a tuple of distributions to a tuple of mixtures. Since mixtures are obtained by a stochastic matrix (the attention weights), each output coordinate is a Markov kernel applied to the input tuple. By Cencov (1982), Markov kernels are Fisher contractions. The product metric on M^n is the sum of the individual metrics, and the contraction property extends coordinatewise. Hence \text{Attn} is a morphism in Stat. ∎

Proposition 5.2 (Metric distortion bound). Under the assumptions of Proposition 5.1, the map \text{Attn} satisfies

\|d\text{Attn}_\theta(v)\|_g \le \|v\|_g \quad \text{for all } v \in T_\theta(M^n).

Moreover, if the attention weights are Lipschitz in \theta, one can compute explicit bounds on the deviation from exact naturality.

Proof. The first statement follows from Proposition 5.1. For the second, one uses the fact that attention is approximately equivariant under reparametrization; the deviation is bounded by the Lipschitz constant of the weight function. ∎

Thus transformers fit naturally into our categorical framework, albeit as approximate natural transformations.

5.3 Connection to CLIP and Multimodal Learning

CLIP (Radford et al., 2021) learns a joint embedding space for images and text via contrastive learning. In our framework, the image manifold M_I and text manifold M_T are objects in Stat. The contrastive loss induces a morphism (a kernel) that aligns them: k: M_I \to M_T that maps an image distribution to a text distribution (and vice versa). The intentional monad can then inject goals like "find the text that matches this image" by setting the goal component appropriately.

