Chapter 6: Formal Verification in Lean

6.1 The Lean Theorem Prover

Lean 4 is an interactive theorem prover with an extensive mathematical library (mathlib). We have formalized core definitions and the Data Processing Inequality (DPI) within our category Stat. The DPI states that for any Markov kernel k: M \to N and any two distributions p,q on M,

D_{KL}(k_* p \parallel k_* q) \le D_{KL}(p \parallel q).

In Riemannian terms, this is equivalent to the information contraction property. Formalizing this in Lean provides a machine‑checked foundation for all subsequent results.

6.2 Key Definitions in Lean

```lean
import Mathlib.Geometry.Manifold.RiemannianMetric
import Mathlib.Probability.Measure.FisherInformation

-- Define a statistical manifold as a Riemannian manifold with a Fisher metric
class StatisticalManifold (M : Type*) [TopologicalSpace M] [ChartedSpace ℝⁿ M]
  extends RiemannianMetric M where
  fisher_metric : RiemannianMetric M -- the Fisher metric
  is_dually_flat : ∀ x : M, DualFlatAt x

-- A morphism in Stat: a Markov kernel that contracts Fisher information
structure StatMorphism (M N : Type*) [StatisticalManifold M] [StatisticalManifold N] where
  kernel : M → ProbabilityMeasure N
  contractive : ∀ (x : M) (v : TangentSpace M x),
    fisher_metric N (pushforward (kernel x) v) ≤ fisher_metric M v

-- The intentional monad with goal space G (a Lie group)
def IntentionalMonad (M G : Type*) [StatisticalManifold M] [LieGroup G]
                     [StatisticalManifold G] := M × G

-- Unit and multiplication
def unit (M G) [StatisticalManifold M] [LieGroup G] (e : G) : M → IntentionalMonad M G :=
  λ m => (m, e)

def mult (M G) [LieGroup G] : IntentionalMonad (IntentionalMonad M G) G → IntentionalMonad M G :=
  λ ((m, g1), g2) => (m, g1 * g2)
```

