Appendix A: Extended Mathematical Preliminaries

In this appendix, we collect the essential mathematical concepts and results that underpin our framework. We assume familiarity with basic differential geometry, information geometry, and category theory, but we provide detailed definitions and properties for completeness.

A.1 Riemannian Geometry

Let M be a smooth manifold. A Riemannian metric g assigns to each point p \in M an inner product g_p: T_pM \times T_pM \to \mathbb{R} that varies smoothly. In local coordinates (x^1,\dots,x^n), we write

g = g_{ij}(x) \, dx^i \otimes dx^j,

where (g_{ij}) is a symmetric positive-definite matrix. The Levi-Civita connection \nabla is the unique torsion-free connection compatible with g, i.e., \nabla g = 0. Its Christoffel symbols are given by

\Gamma^k_{ij} = \frac{1}{2} g^{k\ell} (\partial_i g_{j\ell} + \partial_j g_{i\ell} - \partial_\ell g_{ij}).

The Riemann curvature tensor is defined by

R(X,Y)Z = \nabla_X \nabla_Y Z - \nabla_Y \nabla_X Z - \nabla_{[X,Y]} Z.

In components, R(\partial_i,\partial_j)\partial_k = R_{ijk}^{\;\;\;\; \ell} \partial_\ell. The Ricci curvature is the trace

\operatorname{Ric}(X,Y) = \operatorname{tr}\big( Z \mapsto R(Z,X)Y \big).

For a unit vector v, \operatorname{Ric}(v,v) measures the average sectional curvature of planes containing v.

A geodesic \gamma(t) satisfies \nabla_{\dot\gamma}\dot\gamma = 0. The exponential map \exp_p: T_pM \to M sends a tangent vector v to \gamma_v(1), where \gamma_v is the unique geodesic with \gamma_v(0)=p and \dot\gamma_v(0)=v.

A.2 Information Geometry

Consider a parametric family of probability distributions \{p_\theta : \theta \in \Theta\} with \Theta \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n open. Under suitable regularity conditions, the Fisher information matrix is defined by

g_{ij}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}\!\left[ \partial_i \ell_\theta \, \partial_j \ell_\theta \right],

where \ell_\theta(x) = \log p_\theta(x). This matrix is positive definite and defines a Riemannian metric on \Theta, called the Fisher–Rao metric.

For exponential families of the form

p_\theta(x) = \exp\!\big( \theta \cdot T(x) - \psi(\theta) \big) h(x),

the Fisher metric simplifies to the Hessian of the cumulant function:

g_{ij}(\theta) = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta).

The natural parameters \theta and the expectation parameters \eta = \mathbb{E}_\theta[T(X)] = \nabla \psi(\theta) form dual coordinate systems. The Kullback–Leibler divergence between p_\theta and p_{\theta'} is

D_{KL}(\theta \parallel \theta') = \psi(\theta') + \varphi(\eta) - \theta \cdot \eta',

where \varphi is the Legendre dual of \psi. This divergence generates the metric:

g_{ij}(\theta) = \left. \partial_i \partial_{j'} D_{KL}(\theta \parallel \theta') \right|_{\theta'=\theta}.

A.3 Dually Flat Manifolds

A statistical manifold (M,g,\nabla,\nabla^*) is dually flat if both connections are flat (curvature zero) and are dual with respect to g:

X g(Y,Z) = g(\nabla_X Y, Z) + g(Y, \nabla^*_X Z).

In a dually flat space, there exist affine coordinate systems \theta^i (∇-affine) and \eta_i (∇*-affine) such that

g(\partial_i, \partial^j) = \delta_i^j.

The potentials \psi(\theta) and \varphi(\eta) satisfy

\eta_i = \partial_i \psi(\theta), \quad \theta^i = \partial^i \varphi(\eta), \quad \psi(\theta) + \varphi(\eta) = \theta^i \eta_i.

The KL divergence then takes the canonical form

D_{KL}(\theta \parallel \theta') = \psi(\theta') + \varphi(\eta) - \theta^i \eta_i'.

A.4 Geodesic Convexity

A function f: M \to \mathbb{R} on a Riemannian manifold is geodesically convex if for every geodesic \gamma:[0,1]\to M,

f(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t) f(\gamma(0)) + t f(\gamma(1)).

It is \mu-strongly geodesically convex if there exists \mu > 0 such that

f(\gamma(t)) \le (1-t) f(\gamma(0)) + t f(\gamma(1)) - \frac{\mu}{2} t(1-t) d(\gamma(0),\gamma(1))^2.

This is equivalent to the Hessian condition \nabla^2 f \succeq \mu g in the sense of quadratic forms.

A.5 Gradient Flows

The gradient flow of a smooth function f on a Riemannian manifold is the curve \theta(t) satisfying

\dot{\theta}(t) = -\operatorname{grad}_g f(\theta(t)),

where \operatorname{grad}_g f is the unique vector field with g(\operatorname{grad}_g f, X) = df(X) for all X. In coordinates,

(\operatorname{grad}_g f)^i = g^{ij} \partial_j f.

For a \mu-strongly convex function, the gradient flow converges exponentially to the unique minimizer x^*:

f(x(t)) - f(x^*) \le e^{-2\mu t} \big( f(x(0)) - f(x^*) \big).

A key tool is the Polyak–Łojasiewicz inequality:

\|\operatorname{grad}_g f\|^2_g \ge 2\mu (f - f^*),

which is sufficient for exponential convergence even without full convexity.

A.6 Ricci Curvature and Comparison

For a manifold with Ricci curvature bounded below by \rho g, i.e., \operatorname{Ric} \ge \rho g, the Bakry–Émery condition yields estimates on the Laplacian of distance functions. In particular, for a \mu-strongly convex function V, one can control its evolution along a flow using the inequality

\frac{d}{dt} V(\gamma(t)) \le -\mu V(\gamma(t)) + \frac{L^2}{2} \|\dot\gamma\|^2 + \text{curvature terms},

where the curvature term is positive if \rho is negative. This is used in our composition theorem.

