Appendix C: Category Theory Details

C.1 The Category \mathbf{Stat}

Objects. An object of \mathbf{Stat} is a statistical manifold (M, g, (\nabla, \nabla^*)), where M is a smooth manifold of probability distributions, g is the Fisher–Rao metric, and (\nabla, \nabla^*) are dual torsion‑free connections that make M dually flat.

Morphisms. A morphism k: M \to N is a Markov kernel k: M \times \Sigma_N \to [0,1] such that the induced push‑forward map k_*: \mathcal{P}(M) \to \mathcal{P}(N) satisfies the information contraction property:

k_*^* g_N \preceq g_M,

i.e., for every p \in M and every tangent vector v \in T_pM,

g_N\big( (dk)_p v, (dk)_p v \big) \le g_M(v, v).

Equivalently, the pullback of the Fisher metric on N is pointwise less than or equal to the metric on M.

Composition. Given morphisms k: M \to N and \ell: N \to P, their composition \ell \circ k is defined by the usual composition of Markov kernels:

(\ell \circ k)(p)(A) = \int_N \ell(q)(A) \, k(p)(dq).

The information contraction property is preserved because of the data processing inequality (see Appendix F).

Identity. The identity morphism \operatorname{id}_M: M \to M is the Dirac kernel: \operatorname{id}_M(p) = \delta_p. It is clearly an isometry.

C.2 The Intentional Monad T

Let (\mathcal{G}, *, e) be a Lie monoid equipped with a bi‑invariant Fisher metric (so left and right translations are isometries). Define the endofunctor T: \mathbf{Stat} \to \mathbf{Stat} by

T(M) = M \times \mathcal{G},

with the product Fisher metric g_{M\times\mathcal{G}} = g_M \oplus g_{\mathcal{G}}. For a morphism k: M \to N, define

T(k): M \times \mathcal{G} \to N \times \mathcal{G}, \quad T(k)(m, g) = (k(m), g).

Since k is contracting and the identity on \mathcal{G} is an isometry, T(k) is also contracting.

Unit. The unit \eta_M: M \to T(M) is given by

\eta_M(m) = (m, e).

This is an isometric embedding because the metric on T(M) restricts to g_M on the first factor and the second factor is constant.

Multiplication. The multiplication \mu_M: T(T(M)) = (M \times \mathcal{G}) \times \mathcal{G} \to M \times \mathcal{G} is defined by

\mu_M\big( (m, g_1), g_2 \big) = (m, g_1 * g_2).

Bi‑invariance of the metric on \mathcal{G} ensures that the group operation is an isometry when both factors are varied appropriately, so \mu_M is a morphism in \mathbf{Stat}.

Monad Laws. We verify the monad laws:

· \mu_M \circ T(\eta_M)(m, g) = \mu_M( (\eta_M(m), g) ) = \mu_M( ((m,e), g) ) = (m, e * g) = (m, g).
· \mu_M \circ \eta_{T(M)}(m, g) = \mu_M( ((m,g), e) ) = (m, g * e) = (m, g).
· Associativity: \mu_M \circ T(\mu_M)((m,g_1), g_2, g_3) = \mu_M( (m, g_1 * g_2), g_3 ) = (m, (g_1 * g_2) * g_3) and \mu_M \circ \mu_{T(M)}((m,g_1), g_2, g_3) = \mu_M( (m,g_1), g_2 * g_3 ) = (m, g_1 * (g_2 * g_3)); these are equal by associativity of *.

Thus (T, \eta, \mu) is a monad, specifically the writer monad with values in the monoid \mathcal{G}.

C.3 Kleisli Category \mathbf{Stat}_T

The Kleisli category \mathbf{Stat}_T has the same objects as \mathbf{Stat}. A Kleisli morphism f: M \to N is a morphism f: M \to T(N) in \mathbf{Stat}. Composition of Kleisli morphisms is defined by

g \circ_T f = \mu_Z \circ T(g) \circ f.

This models processes that output both a new state and a goal.

Definition C.1 (Intentional morphism). A Kleisli morphism f: M \to N is called \epsilon-intentional if for every m \in M,

d_M\big( m, \pi_M(f(m)) \big) \le \epsilon,

where \pi_M: T(N) = N \times \mathcal{G} \to N is the projection onto the state component. (Here we implicitly assume that M = N for the distance to be defined; for general M \neq N, the definition requires a common embedding or a cost function. In this thesis we restrict to endomorphisms when discussing intentionality.)

