Appendix D: Information Geometry Computations

D.1 Fisher Metric for Exponential Families

Consider an exponential family

p_\theta(x) = \exp\!\big( \theta \cdot T(x) - \psi(\theta) \big) h(x).

Then

\partial_i \log p_\theta = T_i(x) - \partial_i \psi(\theta).

Hence

g_{ij}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_\theta\!\left[ (T_i - \partial_i \psi)(T_j - \partial_j \psi) \right] = \operatorname{Cov}_\theta(T_i, T_j) = \partial_i \partial_j \psi(\theta).

D.2 Gradient of Entropy

The Shannon entropy is

H(\theta) = -\mathbb{E}_\theta[\log p_\theta(X)] = -\int p_\theta(x) \big( \theta \cdot T(x) - \psi(\theta) + \log h(x) \big) dx = \psi(\theta) - \theta \cdot \eta(\theta) - \mathbb{E}_\theta[\log h(X)].

Differentiating with respect to \theta^j:

\partial_j H = \partial_j \psi - \eta_j - \theta^k \partial_j \eta_k.

But \partial_j \psi = \eta_j and \partial_j \eta_k = \partial_j \partial_k \psi = g_{jk}. Therefore

\partial_j H = - \theta^k g_{jk}.

Now compute the gradient with respect to the Fisher metric:

(\operatorname{grad}_g H)^i = g^{ij} \partial_j H = - g^{ij} \theta^k g_{jk} = - \theta^k \delta^i_k = -\theta^i.

Thus in natural parameters,

\operatorname{grad}_g H = -\theta.

D.3 Regularized Loss and Its Gradient

The regularized loss is

\mathcal{L}_\lambda(\theta) = \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}}(\theta) - \lambda H(\theta).

Its gradient is

\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_\lambda = \operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} - \lambda \operatorname{grad}_g H = \operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} + \lambda \theta.

Therefore the intentional flow equation becomes

\dot{\theta} = -\operatorname{grad}_g \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} - \lambda \theta.

D.4 Geodesic Convexity of the Regularized Loss

From Proposition 2.1, we know that -H is 1-strongly geodesically convex. Hence for any \lambda > 0, -\lambda H is \lambda-strongly convex. If \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} is geodesically convex, then \mathcal{L}_\lambda is \lambda-strongly convex. If \mathcal{L}_{\text{task}} is merely convex but not strongly, we still have \mathcal{L}_\lambda strongly convex due to the entropy term.

D.5 Hessian Computation

The Hessian of a function f with respect to the Levi-Civita connection is \nabla^2 f. In coordinates,

(\nabla^2 f)_{ij} = \partial_i \partial_j f - \Gamma^k_{ij} \partial_k f.

For the Fisher metric on an exponential family, the Christoffel symbols simplify because the metric is the Hessian of \psi. In fact, in the \eta-coordinates (expectation parameters), the metric becomes Euclidean and geodesics are straight lines. Then the Hessian of -H is simply the identity.

