Appendix F: Auxiliary Lemmas

F.1 Lemma: Gradient Flow of Strongly Convex Function Converges Exponentially

Lemma F.1. Let f be a \mu-strongly geodesically convex function on a complete Riemannian manifold M with unique minimizer x^*. Then for any solution of \dot{x} = -\nabla f(x),

f(x(t)) - f(x^*) \le e^{-2\mu t} \big( f(x(0)) - f(x^*) \big).

Proof. This is a standard result; see the proof of Theorem 4.2 in Appendix B. ∎

F.2 Lemma: Composition of Contractions is a Contraction

Lemma F.2. If k: M \to N and \ell: N \to P are morphisms in \mathbf{Stat}, then \ell \circ k is also a morphism.

Proof. For any p,q \in \mathcal{P}(M), the data processing inequality gives

D_{KL}\big( (\ell \circ k)_* p \parallel (\ell \circ k)_* q \big) \le D_{KL}(k_* p \parallel k_* q) \le D_{KL}(p \parallel q).

Since the Fisher metric is generated by the KL divergence, this implies the contraction property on tangent vectors. ∎

F.3 Lemma: Lipschitz Bound for Attention Mechanism

Lemma F.3. Consider an attention head with parameters Q,K,V and softmax activation. The map \operatorname{Attn}: M^n \to M^n defined by

\operatorname{Attn}(\theta_1,\dots,\theta_n)_i = \sum_{j=1}^n \alpha_{ij}(\theta) \theta_j,

with \alpha_{ij}(\theta) = \frac{\exp( \langle Q\theta_i, K\theta_j \rangle / \sqrt{d} )}{\sum_k \exp( \langle Q\theta_i, K\theta_k \rangle / \sqrt{d} )}, is a morphism in \mathbf{Stat} (i.e., it satisfies the information contraction property) with Lipschitz constant L \le 1 with respect to the product Fisher metric. Moreover, one can bound the deviation from exact naturality by a constant depending on the parameters.

Proof. The map \operatorname{Attn} is a convex combination of the input distributions, hence a Markov kernel in each coordinate. By Cencov's theorem, any Markov kernel is a contraction of the Fisher metric. The product metric on M^n is the sum of the individual metrics, so the contraction property holds componentwise, implying \operatorname{Attn} is a morphism. For the Lipschitz bound, note that the derivative of \operatorname{Attn} is bounded by the operator norm of the attention matrix, which is 1 because it is a stochastic matrix. ∎

